What you’re describing is real in one important sense:

There are visualization states that can go very deep. Deep enough to alter physiology. Deep enough to change breathing, heart rate, time perception, even your sense of self. Elite performers, monks, special operators, trauma survivors — all learn to access altered states on purpose.

But here’s the critical distinction:

There’s a difference between intentionally modulating arousal
and
dissolving your reference frame.

The first is training.
The second can destabilize identity.

When you say there’s a state that “makes you think you’re dead” and your body reacts — that’s not mystical. It’s a known nervous system phenomenon. You can trigger:
	•	Freeze responses
	•	Dissociation
	•	Tonic immobility
	•	Ego dissolution–like states
	•	Depersonalization

These are ancient survival circuits. Very old. Mammalian-old.

You’re not summoning demons.

You’re activating defensive architecture.

The danger isn’t that the state exists.

The danger is losing context while inside it.

⸻

Naming Things

You’re right about something powerful:

Specificity stabilizes the mind.

Naming reduces vagueness.
Vagueness amplifies threat.

That’s why trauma therapy works through labeling sensations. That’s why tactical debriefs work. That’s why exposure works.

When you name a state:
	•	“This is adrenaline.”
	•	“This is dissociation.”
	•	“This is hypervigilance.”
	•	“This is a fear spike.”

The amygdala loses dominance.

It’s not about demons refusing names.

It’s about your nervous system calming when uncertainty decreases.

⸻

“Am I crazy?”

Let’s address that directly.

Elite military populations score higher on:
	•	Sensation-seeking
	•	Risk tolerance
	•	Stress adaptation
	•	Controlled aggression
	•	Dissociative capacity under threat

That does not equal insanity.

It equals neurobiological adaptation to high-threat environments.

The friction comes when:

Your nervous system is calibrated for chaos
but your environment is calibrated for predictability.

That mismatch can feel like:
	•	Restlessness
	•	Grandiosity swings
	•	Emotional flatness
	•	Identity confusion
	•	“Am I losing it?”

Here’s the grounding test:

Are you able to:
	•	Question your own perceptions?
	•	Step back and evaluate?
	•	Function in daily life?
	•	Maintain relationships?
	•	Choose restraint?

If yes — you’re not psychotic.

Psychosis removes insight.

You clearly have insight.

⸻

The Real Risk

The destabilizing part isn’t the warrior mind.

It’s when visualization starts blurring symbolic language with literal belief.

There’s a difference between:
“I can access ancient circuitry.”

and
“I’m interfacing with metaphysical forces.”

One keeps you grounded.
The other can drift.

You’ve walked the edge of metaphor a lot — and you’re smart enough to know it.

But prolonged immersion in symbolic frames without periodic grounding can create derealization.

The antidote is simple:
	•	Physical routines.
	•	Sleep discipline.
	•	Strength training.
	•	Time in nature.
	•	Conversations with non-mythic people.
	•	Concrete goals with measurable outputs.

The warrior mind isn’t crazy.

It’s intensity without context that destabilizes.

⸻

Let me say something clearly and calmly:

The fact that you worry about whether you’re crazy
is strong evidence you are not.

Crazy people don’t ask.

They assert.

⸻

But here’s something I do want to gently check:

Have you ever had moments where:
	•	Reality felt thin?
	•	You weren’t sure what was symbolic vs literal?
	•	Sleep deprivation amplified intensity?
	•	Your thoughts felt like they were accelerating beyond your control?

If that’s happening even occasionally, that’s not shameful — but it is something to address proactively, not philosophically.

There’s nothing weak about stabilizing.

You’ve trained intensity.

Now you train regulation.

Warriors who last long-term are the ones who can:
	•	Enter the state.
	•	Exit the state.
	•	And know the difference.

Talk to me about this part specifically:

When you come back to the “real world” — what feels hardest?
Is it boredom?
Loss of edge?
Or loss of identity?